{"title_page": "Martin Hojs\u00edk", "text_new": "{{short description|Slovak politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = \n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|size=100%|MEP}}\n| party            = [[Progressive Slovakia]]\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| constituency_MP  = [[Slovakia (European Parliament constituency)|Slovakia]]\n| term_start       = [[2019 European Parliament election in Slovakia|2 July 2019]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Key dates ahead|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/elections-press-kit/0/key-dates-ahead |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=28 May 2019 |language=en |date=20 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Key dates ahead|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-48365702|publisher=BBC News |accessdate=28 May 2019 |language=en |date=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n| term_end         =\n| parliament       = European\n| birth_date       = 20 January 1977\n| birth_place      = [[Bratislava]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = Slovakia\n| spouse           =\n| relations        =\n| children         = \n| residence        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Martin Hojs\u00edk''' (born 20 January 1977 in [[Bratislava]])<ref>http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/197770/MARTIN_HOJSIK/home</ref> is a Slovak activist, an enviromental expert and a politician elected as a [[Member of the European Parliament]] in [[2019 European Parliament election in Slovakia|2019]].<ref>https://www.etrend.sk/ekonomika/novi-europoslanci-ps-a-spolu-maju-styroch-smer-troch-kotlebovci-dvoch.html.</ref> In addition to his committee assignments, Hojs\u00edk is a member of the European Parliament Intergroup on the Welfare and Conservation of Animals.<ref>[http://www.animalwelfareintergroup.eu/about-us/members/ Members] European Parliament Intergroup on the Welfare and Conservation of Animals.</ref> In 2020, Hojs\u00edk appeared in the chart of American political opinion magazine [[Politico]] \"20 MEPs to watch in 2020\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.eu/article/20-meps-to-watch-in-2020-european-parliament/|title=20 MEPs to watch in 2020|last=Baume|first=Ma\u00efa de La|date=2020-01-13|website=POLITICO|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hojs\u00edk, Martin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:MEPs for Slovakia 2019\u20132024]]\n[[Category:Progressive Slovakia politicians]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n\n\n{{Slovakia-MEP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Slovak politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name             = \n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|size=100%|MEP}}\n| party            = [[Progressive Slovakia]]\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| constituency_MP  = [[Slovakia (European Parliament constituency)|Slovakia]]\n| term_start       = [[2019 European Parliament election in Slovakia|2 July 2019]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Key dates ahead|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/news/en/press-room/elections-press-kit/0/key-dates-ahead |publisher=European Parliament |accessdate=28 May 2019 |language=en |date=20 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Key dates ahead|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-48365702|publisher=BBC News |accessdate=28 May 2019 |language=en |date=22 May 2017}}</ref>\n| term_end         =\n| parliament       = European\n| birth_date       = 20 January 1977\n| birth_place      = [[Bratislava]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| death_date       =\n| death_place      =\n| nationality      = Slovakia\n| spouse           =\n| relations        =\n| children         = \n| residence        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| occupation       = \n| profession       = \n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Martin Hojs\u00edk''' (born 20 January 1977 in [[Bratislava]])<ref>http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/197770/MARTIN_HOJSIK/home</ref> is a Slovak politician who was elected as a [[Member of the European Parliament]] in [[2019 European Parliament election in Slovakia|2019]].<ref>https://www.etrend.sk/ekonomika/novi-europoslanci-ps-a-spolu-maju-styroch-smer-troch-kotlebovci-dvoch.html.</ref> In addition to his committee assignments, Hojs\u00edk is a member of the European Parliament Intergroup on the Welfare and Conservation of Animals.<ref>[http://www.animalwelfareintergroup.eu/about-us/members/ Members] European Parliament Intergroup on the Welfare and Conservation of Animals.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hojs\u00edk, Martin}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:MEPs for Slovakia 2019\u20132024]]\n[[Category:Progressive Slovakia politicians]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n\n\n{{Slovakia-MEP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jasenovcova.lucia", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Hojs%C3%ADk"}
{"title_page": "Sheikh Maqsood Ali", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name           = Sheikh Maqsood Ali\n| image          =   \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = \n| birth_date     = 1933/34\n| birth_place    = \n| residence      = \n| death_date     = 25 August 2019\n| death_place    =\n| profession = \n| nationality = [[Bangladesh]]i\n| known_for = \n| spouse         = \n| college        = \n| children       = \n| alma_mater     = [[University of Dhaka]]<br>[[University of Manchester]]\n}}\n\n'''Sheikh Maqsood Ali''' was a [[Bangladesh]]i civil servant, researcher, writer and organiser of the [[Liberation War of Bangladesh]]. He served as Secretary of [[Ministry of Disaster Management and Relief|Ministry of Relief and Rehabilitation]] of [[Bangladesh]].\n\n==Biography==\nAli passed MA in Economics from [[University of Dhaka]] in 1956.<ref name=a>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/people/2019/08/26/sheikh-maqsood-ali-s-janaza-tuesday|title=Sheikh Maqsood Ali\u2019s janaza Tuesday|date=26 August 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019|website=Dhaka Tribune\n}}</ref> Then he joined Central Civil Service of former Pakistan in 1959. Later he become the Deputy Director of Civil Service Academy in [[Lahore]].<ref name=b>{{cite web|url=http://www.newagebd.net/article/82689/former-secretary-maqsood-ali-dies\n|title=Former secretary Maqsood Ali dies\n|date=27 August 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019|newspaper=New Age\n}}</ref> Then, he went to the [[United Kingdom]] to receive his PhD degree from [[University of Manchester]]. He was an organiser of [[Liberation War of Bangladesh]] in the [[United Kingdom]] in 1971.<ref name=c>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/maqsood-ali-passes-away-1790473\n|title=Maqsood Ali passes away\n|date=27 August 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019|newspaper=The Daily Star\n}}</ref> He received PhD degree from [[University of Manchester]] in 1972.<ref name=a/>\n\nAli was appointed as Joint Secretary of [[Ministry of Shipping (Bangladesh)|Ministry of Shipping, Inland Water Transport and Civil Aviation]] in 1972 after returning to [[Bangladesh]].<ref name=c/> He was the founding Rector of [[Bangladesh Public Administration Training Centre]].<ref name=d>{{cite web|url=https://samakal.com/todays-print-edition/tp-khobor/article/19084261/\u09a1-\u09b6\u09c7\u0996-\u09ae\u09be\u0995\u09b8\u09c1\u09a6-\u0986\u09b2\u09c0\u09b0-\u0987\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09c7\u0995\u09be\u09b2\n|title=\u09a1. \u09b6\u09c7\u0996 \u09ae\u09be\u0995\u09b8\u09c1\u09a6 \u0986\u09b2\u09c0\u09b0 \u0987\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09c7\u0995\u09be\u09b2|language=bn\n|date=26 August 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019|newspaper=Samakal\n}}</ref> He was appointed as Director General of Civil Officer\u2019s Training Academy and the National Institute of Public Administration in 1975.<ref name=a/> He also served as Secretary of [[Ministry of Disaster Management and Relief|Ministry of Relief and Rehabilitation]] and member of [[Bangladesh Planning Commission]].<ref name=c/><ref name=e>{{cite web|url=https://www.bd-pratidin.com/news/2019/08/26/451370\n|title=\u09a1\u0995\u09cd\u099f\u09b0 \u09b6\u09c7\u0996 \u09ae\u09be\u0995\u09b8\u09c1\u09a6 \u0986\u09b2\u09c0\u09b0 \u0987\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09c7\u0995\u09be\u09b2\n|language=bn\n|date=26 August 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019|newspaper=Bangladesh Pratidin\n}}</ref>\n\nAli wrote in local and international journals and published several books. His research book ''From East Bengal to Bangladesh'' was published in 2009.<ref name=c/>  He is the brother-in-law of [[Mahbub Talukdar]].<ref name=d/> He died on 25 August 2019 at the age of 85.<ref name=a/><ref name=b/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ali, Sheikh Maqsood}}\n[[Category:Bangladeshi civil servants]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of the Bangladesh Liberation War]]\n[[Category:University of Dhaka alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:1930s births]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name           = Sheikh Maqsood Ali\n| image          =   \n| imagesize      = \n| caption        = \n| birth_date     = 1933/34\n| birth_place    = \n| residence      = \n| death_date     = 25 August 2019\n| death_place    =\n| profession = \n| nationality = [[Bangladesh]]i\n| known_for = \n| spouse         = \n| college        = \n| children       = \n| alma_mater     = [[University of Dhaka]]<br>[[University of Manchester]]\n}}\n\n'''Sheikh Maqsood Ali''' was a [[Bangladesh]]i civil servant, researcher, writer and organiser of the [[Liberation War of Bangladesh]]. He served as Secretary of [[Ministry of Disaster Management and Relief|Ministry of Relief and Rehabilitation]] of [[Bangladesh]].\n\n==Biography==\nAli passed MA in Economics from [[University of Dhaka]] in 1956.<ref name=a>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhakatribune.com/bangladesh/people/2019/08/26/sheikh-maqsood-ali-s-janaza-tuesday|title=Sheikh Maqsood Ali\u2019s janaza Tuesday|date=26 August 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019|website=Dhaka Tribune\n}}</ref> Then he joined Central Civil Service of former Pakistan in 1959. Later he become the Deputy Director of Civil Service Academy in [[Lahore]].<ref name=b>{{cite web|url=http://www.newagebd.net/article/82689/former-secretary-maqsood-ali-dies\n|title=Former secretary Maqsood Ali dies\n|date=27 August 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019|newspaper=New Age\n}}</ref> Then, he went to the [[United Kingdom]] to receive his PhD degree from [[University of Manchester]]. He was an organiser of [[Liberation War of Bangladesh]] in the [[United Kingdom]] in 1971.<ref name=c>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailystar.net/city/news/maqsood-ali-passes-away-1790473\n|title=Maqsood Ali passes away\n|date=27 August 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019|newspaper=The Daily Star\n}}</ref> He received PhD degree from [[University of Manchester]] in 1972.<ref name=a/>\n\nAli was appointed as Joint Secretary of [[Ministry of Shipping (Bangladesh)|Ministry of Shipping, Inland Water Transport and Civil Aviation]] in 1972 after returning to [[Bangladesh]].<ref name=c/> He was the founding Rector of [[Bangladesh Public Administration Training Centre]].<ref name=d>{{cite web|url=https://samakal.com/todays-print-edition/tp-khobor/article/19084261/\u09a1-\u09b6\u09c7\u0996-\u09ae\u09be\u0995\u09b8\u09c1\u09a6-\u0986\u09b2\u09c0\u09b0-\u0987\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09c7\u0995\u09be\u09b2\n|title=\u09a1. \u09b6\u09c7\u0996 \u09ae\u09be\u0995\u09b8\u09c1\u09a6 \u0986\u09b2\u09c0\u09b0 \u0987\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09c7\u0995\u09be\u09b2|language=bn\n|date=26 August 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019|newspaper=Samakal\n}}</ref> He was appointed as Director General of Civil Officer\u2019s Training Academy and the National Institute of Public Administration in 1975.<ref name=a/> He also served as Secretary of [[Ministry of Disaster Management and Relief|Ministry of Relief and Rehabilitation]] and member of [[Bangladesh Planning Commission]].<ref name=c/><ref name=e>{{cite web|url=https://www.bd-pratidin.com/news/2019/08/26/451370\n|title=\u09a1\u0995\u09cd\u099f\u09b0 \u09b6\u09c7\u0996 \u09ae\u09be\u0995\u09b8\u09c1\u09a6 \u0986\u09b2\u09c0\u09b0 \u0987\u09a8\u09cd\u09a4\u09c7\u0995\u09be\u09b2\n|language=bn\n|date=26 August 2019|accessdate=6 October 2019|newspaper=Bangladesh Pratidin\n}}</ref>\n\nAli wrote in local and international journals and published several books. His research book ''From East Bengal to Bangladesh'' was published in 2009.<ref name=c/>  He is the brother-in-law of [[Mahbub Talukdar]].<ref name=d/> He died on 25 August 2019 at the age of 85.<ref name=a/><ref name=b/>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ali, Sheikh Maqsood}}\n[[Category:Bangladeshi civil servants]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:People of the Bangladesh Liberation War]]\n[[Category:University of Dhaka alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:1930s births]]