tic}}|40.2% ''1,328''\n| style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|9.5% ''314''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Bond County, Illinois]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://bondcountyil.com/Home.html County Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070310144543/http://www.cyberdriveillinois.com/departments/archives/irad/edgar.html United States Census Bureau 2007 TIGER/Line Shapefiles]\n* [http://geonames.usgs.gov/domestic/ United States Board on Geographic Names (GNIS)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081205020547/http://www.nationalatlas.gov/ United States National Atlas]\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Bond County, Illinois\n|North     = [[Montgomery County, Illinois|Montgomery County]]\n|Northeast = \n|East      = [[Fayette County, Illinois|Fayette County]]\n|Southeast = \n|South     = [[Clinton County, Illinois|Clinton County]]\n|Southwest = \n|West      = [[Madison County, Illinois|Madison County]]\n|Northwest = \n}}\n\n{{Bond County, Illinois}}\n{{Metro-East}}\n{{Illinois}}\n\n{{coord|38.88|-89.44|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-IL_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Illinois counties]]\n[[Category:Bond County, Illinois]]\n[[Category:1817 establishments in Illinois Territory]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1817]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Underground Railroad]]\n[[Category:Pre-statehood history of Illinois]]\n", "name_user": "Whoisjohngalt", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bond_County,_Illinois"}
{"title_page": "Warez scene", "text_new": "[[File:Warez Hierarchy.svg|thumb|150px|Warez hierarchy]]\nThe '''Warez scene''', often referred to as '''The Scene''',<ref>{{cite book |first=Linus |last=Walleij |title=Copyright does not exist |date=1998 |translator-first=Daniel A. |translator-last=\u00d8ien|chapter=Chapter 5 \u2013 Subculture of the Subcultures |chapter-url=http://svenskefaen.no/cdne/ch5web.htm |url=http://www.devili.iki.fi/pub/misc/books/cdne.pdf |quote=The Scene (capital S) is thus a label for the large group of users that exchange programs (primarily games) and also so-called demos.}}</ref> is an [[Underground economy|underground]] community of people that specialize in the distribution of [[warez]]: copyrighted material, including television shows and series, movies, music, music videos, games, applications, ebooks, and pornography. The Scene is meant to be hidden from the public, only being shared with those within the community. However, as files were commonly leaked outside the community and their popularity grew, some individuals from The Scene began leaking files and uploading them to filehosts, [[BitTorrent (protocol)|torrents]] and [[EDonkey network|ed2k]].\n\nThe Scene has no central leadership, location, or other organizational conventions. The groups themselves create a [[Standard (warez)|ruleset]] for each Scene category (for example, MP3 or TV) that then becomes the active rules for encoding material. These rulesets include a rigid set of requirements that [[warez group]]s (grps) must follow in releasing and managing material. The groups must follow these rules when uploading material, and if the release has a technical error or breaks a rule, other groups may \"[[Nuke (warez)|nuke]]\" (flag as bad content) the release. Groups are in constant competition to get releases up as fast as possible, even though there are no real \"rewards\" for their work (except for access to The Scene). First appearing around the time of [[Bulletin board system|BBS]]es, The Scene is composed primarily of people dealing with and distributing media content for which special skills and advanced software are required.\n\n==History==\nThe warez scene started emerging in the 1970s, used by predecessors of [[software cracking]] and reverse engineering groups. Their work was made available on privately run bulletin board systems (BBSes).<ref name=\"TheWarezSceneHistory\">{{cite web |url=http://www.defacto2.net/wayback/apollo-x-demo-resources-1999-december-17/wrzhst.htm |title=The History of the Warez Scene (unfinished) |accessdate=2012-07-07}}</ref> The first BBSes were located in the U.S., but similar boards started appearing in Canada, the United Kingdom, Australia, and mainland Europe. At the time, setting up a machine capable of distributing data was not trivial and required a certain amount of technical skill.  The reason it was usually done was for technical challenge. The BBSes typically hosted several megabytes of material. The best boards had multiple phone lines and up to one hundred megabytes of storage space, which was very expensive at the time.<ref name=\"WarezWars\">{{cite news |first=David |last=McCandless |title=Warez Wars |url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/5.04/ff_warez.html |publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date = April 1997|accessdate=2009-06-06}}</ref> Releases were mostly games and later software.\n\nAs the world of software development evolved to counter the distribution of material and as the software and hardware needed for distribution became readily available to anyone, The Scene adapted to the changes and turned from simple distribution to actual cracking of the protections and non-commercial reverse engineering.<ref name=\"TheWarezSceneHistory\" /> As many groups of people who wanted to do this emerged, a requirement for promotion of individual groups became evident, which prompted the evolution of the [[Artscene]], which specialized in the creation of graphical [[art]] associated with individual groups.<ref name=\"DefactoSceneHistory\">{{cite web |url=http://www.defacto2.net/includes/documentsweb/df2web99/scene-archive/history.html | title=scene history | accessdate=2009-06-06}}</ref> The groups would promote their abilities with ever more sophisticated and advanced software, graphical art, and later also music ([[demoscene]]).<ref>[http://www.bbsdocumentary.com/ The BBS Documentary \u2013 MOVIE]</ref>\n\nThe subcommunities (artscene, demoscene, etc.), which were doing nothing illegal, eventually branched off. The programs containing the group promotional material (coding/graphical/musical presentations) evolved to become separate programs distributed through The Scene and were nicknamed [[demo (computer programming)|Intro]]s and later [[Cracktro]]s.\n\nThe [[demoscene]] grew especially strong in [[Scandinavia]], where annual gatherings are hosted.<ref>{{cite web |\ntitle=ASSEMBLY Summer 2011 \u2013 Finland's largest computer festival in Helsinki |\nurl=http://www.assembly.org |\nyear=2011}}</ref>\n\n==Release procedure==\nWhen releasing material, groups must first encode properly so as not to be nuked, which shows up as a cautionary flag to potential users. After encoding, they upload the files to a [[Topsite (warez)|topsite]] that is a [[FTP]] server where all the files originate. When the upload is complete, they execute a command that causes the name and category of the release to be announced in the topsite's [[Internet Relay Chat|IRC]] channel. New releases are also announced 0sec (meaning seconds to minutes after official scene pre) on various public websites.<ref>{{cite web |title=NFORush.net \u2013 Pre Announces |url=http://nforush.net/new-scene-releases.html}}</ref> This is called a \"pre\" release. Once this is done, all other releases for the same material are nuked as duplicates (\"dupes\"). However, if there is a technical error or the file breaks the ruleset for the category, the original \"pre\" release will be nuked. Other groups then encode the same material and release it with a \"PROPER\" tag in the filename. The same group may re-encode the file, with the new release marked as \"REPACK\". This FTP server and IRC are hidden and closed to the public.\n\nEach release in The Scene consists of a folder containing the material (sometimes split into [[RAR (file format)|RAR]] pieces), plus an [[.nfo|NFO]] and [[.sfv|SFV]] file. The NFO is a text file which has essential information about the files encoded, including a reason for the nuke if the file is a PROPER or REPACK release. A robust NFO file may contain a group's mission statement, recruitment requirements, greetings, and contact info; many groups have a standard [[ASCII art]] template for the file, with the most prolific exhibiting elaborate artistic examples. The SFV file uses [[checksums]] to ensure that the files of a release are working properly and have not been damaged or tampered with. This is typically done with the aid of an external executable like QuickSFV or SFV Checker. Failure to include an NFO or SFV file in the release will generally result in a nuke, as these are essential components of the [[standard (warez)|warez standard]] to which The Scene adheres.\n\nIn 2012, the Scene had over 100 active groups releasing material. Over 1,000 releases are made each day, with a cumulative total of more than five million releases through 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=PreDB.in |url=http://predb.in/doku/index.htm#stats}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Database.with.5.million.Releases-YUNOLEECH |date=2012-06-03 |author=YUNOLEECH |quote=pre database with about 5 million releases |url=http://scenenotice.org/details.php?id=2110 |work=SceneNotice.org}}</ref>\n\n==Crackers and reverse engineers==\n{{Main|Software cracking}}\nCracking has been the core element of The Scene since its beginning. This part of The Scene community specializes in the creation of software cracks and [[keygen]]s. The challenge of cracking and reverse engineering complicated software is what makes it an attraction.<ref name=Craig2005>\n{{cite book |last1=Craig |first1=Paul |last2=Honick |first2=Ron |editor-first=Mark |editor-last=Burnett |title=Software Piracy Exposed \u2013 Secrets from the Dark Side Revealed |date=April 2005 |publisher=Syngress Publishing |location=United States of America |isbn=1-932266-98-4 |doi=10.1016/B978-193226698-6/50029-5 |page=[https://archive.org/details/softwarepiracyex0000crai/page/63 63] |chapter=Chapter 4: Cracking |quote=For many, it is the challenge of the game; trying to defeat technology designed specifically to stop them. For others, there is a significant financial incentive involved. Many black market counterfeiting operations employ crackers to remove copy protection from software titles, thereby allowing the material to be copied and sold. Cracking is taken very seriously, and is the most respected role in the warez group scene. |lay-url=http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/bookdescription.cws_home/705731/description |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/softwarepiracyex0000crai/page/63 }}</ref> The game cracking group [[List of warez groups#SKIDROW|SKIDROW]] described it as follows in one of their NFO files:<ref>{{citation |title=Trainz.Simulator.12.Nfo.Fix-SKIDROW |date=2011-04-18}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Keep in mind we do all this, because we can and because we like the thrilling excitement of winning over the other competing groups. We absolutely don't do all these releases, to please the general user that rather want to spend their cash on updating to the latest hardware, and sees the scene releases as a source to play all these games for free. Enjoy playing and remember if you like it, support the developer!}}\n\nThe game ripping group [[Myth (warez)|MYTH]] expressed it as follows in their NFO files:<ref>{{citation |title=Yager.DVDRiP-MYTH |date=2003-09-25}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|We do this just for FUN. We are against any profit or commercialisation of piracy. We do not spread any release, others do that. In fact, we BUY all our own games with our own hard earned and worked for efforts. Which is from our own real life non-scene jobs. As we love game originals. Nothing beats a quality original.  \"If you like this game, BUY it. We did!\"}}\n\nDavid Grime, former [[DrinkOrDie]] member, describes the motivation of the warez scene as follows: \"It's all about stature. They are just trying to make a name for themselves for no reason other than self-gratification.\"<ref name=\"spoils\">{{cite web |title=Pirates on the Web, Spoils on the Street |first=Jennifer |last=Lee |date=2002-07-11 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/11/technology/circuits/11WARE.html?pagewanted=all |website=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Chandra2016\">{{cite book|last1=Chandra|first1=Priyank|title=Proceedings of the 2016 CHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems \u2013 CHI '16|chapter=Order in the Warez Scene|year=2016|pages=372\u2013383|doi=10.1145/2858036.2858341|isbn=9781450333627}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Legal aspects of file sharing]]\n* [[Copyright infringement]]\n* [[Crack intro]]\n* [[FXP board]]\n* [[Topsite (warez)|Topsite]]\n* [[Standard (warez)]]\n* ''[[The Scene (miniseries)|The Scene]]'' \u2013 miniseries\n* ''[[How Music Got Free]]'' \u2013 book by Stephen Witt\n* [[List of warez groups]]\n* [[SCA (computer virus)]] \u2013 first computer virus for the Commodore Amiga, created by Swiss Cracking Association<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gotpapers.untergrund.net/?p=1307 |title=The Movers Collection, Part 2 |website=got papers? |date=2016-01-27 |quote=SCA sending out custom-made anti-virus software to protect their friends from their own SCA Virus}}</ref>\n* [[Twilight (CD-ROM)|Twilight]] \u2013 pressed warez disks sold in the Netherlands in the late nineties using scene releases\n* [[I Am... (Nas album)|''I Am...'' (Nas album)]] \u2013 one of the first major label releases to be widely leaked using MP3 technology.<!-- Nas-I_Am_Advanced_Promo-Apc-Traxter January 3rd, 1999\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uwVUIdraIhA&t=4392 \"That was the first time a rap artist ever made an MP3 dissing a ripping group\" -->\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n<!-- to be used for referencing and/or adding content -->\n* {{cite thesis |type=Ph.D. |first=Lars |last=Rau |title=Ph\u00e4nomenologie und Bek\u00e4mpfung von \"Cyberpiraterie\": eine kriminologische und kriminalpolitische Analyse |date=2004-10-22 |publisher=Justus-Liebig-Universit\u00e4t |language=German |trans-title=Phenomenology and combat \"cyber piracy\": a criminological and criminal policy analysis |isbn=3-86537-246-5 |url=http://geb.uni-giessen.de/geb/volltexte/2004/1819| accessdate=2013-07-27}}\n* {{cite thesis |first=Jan Adriaan |last=van der Wal |title=The \"rise\" and \"fall\" of the MP3scene: A Global and Virtual Organization - An organizational, social relational and technological analysis |year=2009 |url=http://dare.uva.nl/document/139360}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Explaining the rise and fall of the Warez MP3 scene: An empirical account from the inside |first1=Ard |last1=Huizing |first2=Jan A. |last2=van der Wal |url=http://firstmonday.org/ojs/index.php/fm/article/view/5546/4125 |journal=First Monday |volume=19 |issue=10 |date=2014-10-06 |doi=10.5210/fm.v19i10.5546 |issn=1396-0466}}\n* {{cite book |author=Hitzler, R., Niederbacher, A. |title=Leben in Szenen: Formen Juveniler Vergemeinschaftung Heute |trans-title=Living in Scenes. Forms of Youth Communities |language=German |year=2010 |publisher=VS Verlag f\u00fcr Sozialwissenschaften GmbH |isbn=9783531925325 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GNsdBAAAQBAJ |accessdate=2013-06-23}}\n* {{cite thesis |type=Ph.D. |first=Andrew |last=Sockanathan |year=2011 |title=Digital Desire and Recorded Music: OiNK, Mnemotechnics and the Private BitTorrent Architecture |publisher=Goldsmiths, University of London, Centre for Cultural Studies |url=http://research.gold.ac.uk/6569/}}\n* {{cite journal |url=http://widerscreen.fi/numerot/2014-1-2/amis-euros-software-import-contacts-european-american-cracking-scenes/ |title=\"Amis and Euros.\" Software Import and Contacts Between European and American Cracking Scenes |first=Patryk |last=Wasiak |date=2014-04-15 |journal=WiderScreen |issue=1\u20132}}\n* {{cite web |author=Ernesto |date=2009-02-20 |url=http://torrentfreak.com/anakata-explains-in-court-how-the-scene-works-090220/ |title=Anakata Explains in Court How 'The Scene' Works}}\n* {{cite journal |first=Patryk |last=Wasiak |date=2012 |title='Illegal Guys'. A History of Digital Subcultures in Europe during the 1980s |journal=Zeithistorische Forschungen/Studies in Contemporary History, Online-Ausgabe |url=http://www.zeithistorische-forschungen.de/2-2012/id=4746 |pages=257\u2013276 |volume=9 |issue=2}}\n* {{cite web |first=Gavin |last=Mueller |date=2014 |url=https://www.academia.edu/7870503 |title=The Social Ecology of Early Software Piracy}} Presentation at the 2014 Cultural Studies Association conference in Salt Lake City.\n* Stephen Witt, ''[[How Music Got Free: The End of an Industry, the Turn of the Century, and the Patient Zero of Piracy]]'', Viking (June 16, 2015), hardcover, 304 pages, {{ISBN|978-0525426615}}\n* {{cite book |last=Maher |first=Jimmy |title=The Future Was Here: The Commodore Amiga |year=2012 |isbn=9780262017206 |publisher=The MIT Press |chapter=Chapter 7: The Scene}}\n* {{cite web |first=Jimmy |last=Maher |title=A Pirate's Life for Me, Part 2: The Scene |url=http://www.filfre.net/2016/01/a-pirates-life-for-me-part-2-the-scene/ |date=2016-01-01 |website=The Digital Antiquarian}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BXBqUBAv1ek Scene history] in video on [[YouTube]]\n* [http://www.atlantis-prophecy.org/recollection The Recollection Magazine] \u2013 Recollections of the early scene.\n* [http://www.atlantis-prophecy.org/mags Ultimate C64 Scene Mag Archive] \u2013 Collection of C64 disk and paper magazines.\n<!--* [ftp://ftp.shroo.ms/warezscene/ Shroo.ms FTP archive] - Archive of scene nfo files and magazines.-->\n\n{{Independent production}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Warez Scene}}\n[[Category:Copyright infringement]]\n[[Category:Warez]]\n[[Category:Subcultures]]\n[[Category:File sharing communities]]\n[[Category:Hacker culture]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Warez Hierarchy.svg|thumb|150px|Warez hierarchy]]\nThe '''Warez scene''', often referred to as '''The Scene''',<ref>{{cite book |first=Linus |last=Walleij |title=Copyright does not exist |date=1998 |translator-first=Daniel A. |translator-last=\u00d8ien|chapter=Chapter 5 \u2013 Subculture of the Subcultures |chapter-url=http://svenskefaen.no/cdne/ch5web.htm |url=http://www.devili.iki.fi/pub/misc/books/cdne.pdf |quote=The Scene (capital S) is thus a label for the large group of users that exchange programs (primarily games) and also so-called demos.}}</ref> is an [[Underground economy|underground]] community of people that specialize in the distribution of [[warez]]: copyrighted material, including television shows and series, movies, music, music videos, games, applications, ebooks, and pornography. The Scene is meant to be hidden from the public, only being shared with those within the community. However, as files were commonly leaked outside the community and their popularity grew, some individuals from The Scene began leaking files and uploading them to filehosts, [[BitTorrent (protocol)|torrents]] and [[EDonkey network|ed2k]].\n\nThe Scene has no central leadership, location, or other organizational conventions. The groups themselves create a [[Standard (warez)|ruleset]] for each Scene category (for example, MP3 or TV) that then becomes the active rules for encoding material. These rulesets include a rigid set of requirements that [[warez group]]s (grps) must follow in releasing and managing material. The groups must follow these rules when uploading material, and if the release has a technical error or breaks a rule, other groups may \"[[Nuke (warez)|nuke]]\" (flag as bad content) the release. Groups are in constant competition to get releases up as fast as possible, even though there are no real \"rewards\" for their work (except for access to The Scene). First appearing around the time of [[Bulletin board system|BBS]]es, The Scene is composed primarily of people dealing with and distributing media content for which special skills and advanced software are required.\n\n==History==\nThe warez scene started emerging in the 1970s, used by predecessors of [[software cracking]] and reverse engineering groups. Their work was made available on privately run bulletin board systems (BBSes).<ref name=\"TheWarezSceneHistory\">{{cite web |url=http://www.defacto2.net/wayback/apollo-x-demo-resources-1999-december-17/wrzhst.htm |title=The History of the Warez Scene (unfinished) |accessdate=2012-07-07}}</ref> The first BBSes were located in the U.S., but similar boards started appearing in Canada, the United Kingdom, Australia, and mainland Europe. At the time, setting up a machine capable of distributing data was not trivial and required a certain amount of technical skill.  The reason it was usually done was for technical challenge. The BBSes typically hosted several megabytes of material. The best boards had multiple phone lines and up to one hundred megabytes of storage space, which was very expensive at the time.<ref name=\"WarezWars\">{{cite news |first=David |last=McCandless |title=Warez Wars |url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/5.04/ff_warez.html |publisher=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |date = April 1997|accessdate=2009-06-06}}</ref> Releases were mostly games and later software.\n\nAs the world of software development evolved to counter the distribution of material and as the software and hardware needed for distribution became readily available to anyone, The Scene adapted to the changes and turned from simple distribution to actual cracking of the protections and non-commercial reverse engineering.<ref name=\"TheWarezSceneHistory\" /> As many groups of people who wanted to do this emerged, a requirement for promotion of individual groups became evident, which prompted the evolution of the [[Artscene]], which specialized in the creation of graphical [[art]] associated with individual groups.<ref name=\"DefactoSceneHistory\">{{cite web |url=http://www.defacto2.net/includes/documentsweb/df2web99/scene-archive/history.html | title=scene history | accessdate=2009-06-06}}</ref> The groups would promote their abilities with ever more sophisticated and advanced software, graphical art, and later also music ([[demoscene]]).<ref>[http://www.bbsdocumentary.com/ The BBS Documentary \u2013 MOVIE]</ref>\n\nThe subcommunities (artscene, demoscene, etc.), which were doing nothing illegal, eventually branched off. The programs containing the group promotional material (coding/graphical/musical presentations) evolved to become separate programs distributed through The Scene and were nicknamed [[demo (computer programming)|Intro]]s and later [[Cracktro]]s.\n\nThe [[demoscene]] grew especially strong in [[Scandinavia]], where annual gatherings are hosted.<ref>{{cite web |\ntitle=ASSEMBLY Summer 2011 \u2013 Finland's largest computer festival in Helsinki |\nurl=http://www.assembly.org |\nyear=2011}}</ref>\n\n==Release procedure==\nWhen releasing material, groups must first encode properly so as not to be nuked, which shows up as a cautionary flag to potential users. After encoding, they upload the files to a [[Topsite (warez)|topsite]] that is a [[FTP]] server where all the files originate. When the upload is complete, they execute a command that causes the name and category of the release to be announced in the topsite's [[Internet Relay Chat|IRC]] channel. New releases are also announced 0sec (meaning seconds to minutes after official scene pre) on various public websites.<ref>{{cite web |title=NFORush.net \u2013 Pre Announces |url=http://nforush.net/new-scene-releases.html}}</ref> This is called a \"pre\" release. Once this is done, all other releases for the same material are nuked as duplicates (\"dupes\"). However, if there is a technical error or the file breaks the ruleset for the category, the original \"pre\" release will be nuked. Other groups then encode the same material and release it with a \"PROPER\" tag in the filename. The same group may re-encode the file, with the new release marked as \"REPACK\". This FTP server and IRC are hidden and closed to the public.\n\nEach release in The Scene consists of a folder containing the material (sometimes split into [[RAR (file format)|RAR]] pieces), plus an [[.nfo|NFO]] and [[.sfv|SFV]] file. The NFO is a text file which has essential information about the files encoded, including a reason for the nuke if the file is a PROPER or REPACK release. A robust NFO file may contain a group's mission statement, recruitment requirements, greetings, and contact info; many groups have a standard [[ASCII art]] template for the file, with the most prolific exhibiting elaborate artistic examples. The SFV file uses [[checksums]] to ensure that the files of a release are working properly and have not been damaged or tampered with. This is typically done with the aid of an external executable like QuickSFV or SFV Checker. Failure to include an NFO or SFV file in the release will generally result in a nuke, as these are essential components of the [[standard (warez)|warez standard]] to which The Scene adheres.\n\nIn 2012, the Scene had over 100 active groups releasing material. Over 1,000 releases are made each day, with a cumulative total of more than five million releases through 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=PreDB.in |url=http://predb.in/doku/index.htm#stats}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Database.with.5.million.Releases-YUNOLEECH |date=2012-06-03 |author=YUNOLEECH |quote=pre database with about 5 million releases |url=http://scenenotice.org/details.php?id=2110 |work=SceneNotice.org}}</ref>\n\n==Crackers and reverse engineers==\n{{Main|Software cracking}}\nCracking has been the core element of The Scene since its beginning. This part of The Scene community specializes in the creation of software cracks and [[keygen]]s. The challenge of cracking and reverse engineering complicated software is what makes it an attraction.<ref name=Craig2005>\n{{cite book |last1=Craig |first1=Paul |last2=Honick |first2=Ron |editor-first=Mark |editor-last=Burnett |title=Software Piracy Exposed \u2013 Secrets from the Dark Side Revealed |date=April 2005 |publisher=Syngress Publishing |location=United States of America |isbn=1-932266-98-4 |doi=10.1016/B978-193226698-6/50029-5 |page=[https://archive.org/details/softwarepiracyex0000crai/page/63 63] |chapter=Chapter 4: Cracking |quote=For many, it is the challenge of the game; trying to defeat technology designed specifically to stop them. For others, there is a significant financial incentive involved. Many black market counterfeiting operations employ crackers to remove copy protection from software titles, thereby allowing the material to be copied and sold. Cracking is taken very seriously, and is the most respected role in the warez group scene. |lay-url=http://www.elsevier.com/wps/find/bookdescription.cws_home/705731/description |chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/softwarepiracyex0000crai/page/63 }}</ref> The game cracking group [[List of warez groups#SKIDROW|SKIDROW]] described it as follows in one of their NFO files:<ref>{{citation |title=Trainz.Simulator.12.Nfo.Fix-SKIDROW |date=2011-04-18}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|Keep in mind we do all this, because we can and because we like the thrilling excitement of winning over the other competing groups. We absolutely don't do all these releases, to please the general user that rather want to spend their cash on updating to the latest hardware, and sees the scene releases as a source to play all these games for free. Enjoy playing and remember if you like it, support the developer!}}\n\nThe game ripping group [[Myth (warez)|MYTH]] expressed it as follows in their NFO files:<ref>{{citation |title=Yager.DVDRiP-MYTH |date=2003-09-25}}</ref>\n\n{{quote|We do this just for FUN. We are against any profit or commercialisation of piracy. We do not spread any release, others do that. In fact, we BUY all our own games with our own hard earned and worked for efforts. Which is from our own real life non-scene jobs. As we love game originals. Nothing beats a quality original.  \"If you like this game, BUY it. We did!\"}}\n\nDavid Grime, former [[DrinkOrDie]] member, describes the motivation of the warez scene as follows: \"It's all about stature. They are just trying to make a name for themselves for no reason other than self-gratification.\"<ref name=\"spoils\">{{cite web |title=Pirates on the Web, Spoils on the Street |first=Jennifer |last=Lee |date=2002-07-11 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/11/technology/circuits/11WARE.html?pagewanted=all |website=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Chandra2016\">{{cite book|last1=Chandra|first1=Priyank|title=Proceedings of the 2016 CHI Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems \u2013 CHI '16|chapter=Order in the Warez Scene|year=2016|pages=372\u2013383|doi=10.1145/2858036.2858341|isbn=9781450333627}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Legal aspects of file sharing]]\n* [[Copyright infringement]]\n* [[Crack intro]]\n* [[FXP board]]\n* [[Topsite (warez)|Topsite]]\n* [[Standard (warez)]]\n* ''[[The Scene (miniseries)|The Scene]]'' \u2013 miniseries\n* ''[[How Music Got Free]]'' \u2013 book by Stephen Witt\n* [[List of warez groups]]\n* [[SCA (computer virus)]] \u2013 first computer virus for the Commodore Amiga, created by Swiss Cracking Association<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gotpapers.untergrund.net/?p=1307 |title=The Movers Collection, Part 2 |website=got papers? |date=2016-01-27 |quote=SCA sending out custom-made anti-virus software to protect their friends from their own SCA Virus}}</ref>\n* [[Twilight (CD-ROM)|Twilight]] \u2013 pressed warez disks sold in the Netherlands in the late nineties using scene releases\n* [[I Am... (Nas album)|''I Am...'' (Nas album)]] \u2013 one of the first major label releases to be widely leaked using MP3 technology.<!-- Nas-I_Am_Advanced_Promo-Apc-Traxter January 3rd, 1999\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uwVUIdraIhA&t=4392 \"That was the first time a rap artist ever made an MP3 dissing a ripping group\" -->\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n<!-- to be used for referencing and/or adding content -->\n* {{cite thesis |type=Ph.D. |first=Lars |last=Rau |title=Ph\u00e4nomenologie und Bek\u00e4mpfung von \"Cyberpiraterie\": eine kriminologische und kriminalpolitische Analyse |date=2004-10-22 |publisher=Justus-Liebig-Universit\u00e4t |language=German |trans-title=Phenomenology and combat \"cyber piracy\": a criminological and criminal policy analysis |isbn=3-86537-246-5 |url=http://geb.uni-giessen.de/geb/volltexte/2004/1819| accessdate=2013-07-27}}\n* {{cite thesis |first=Jan Adriaan |last=van der Wal |title=The \"rise\" and \"fall\" of the MP3scene: A Global and Virtual Organization - An organizational, social relational and technological analysis |year=2009 |url=http://dare.uva.nl/document/139360}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Explaining the rise and fall of the Warez MP3 scene: An empirical account from the inside |first1=Ard |last1=Huizing |first2=Jan A. |last2=van der Wal |url=http://firstmonday.org/ojs/index.php/fm/article/view/5546/4125 |journal=First Monday |volume=19 |issue=10 |date=2014-10-06 |doi=10.5210/fm.v19i10.5546 |issn=1396-0466}}\n* {{cite book |author=Hitzler, R., Niederbacher, A. |title=Leben in Szenen: Formen Juveniler Vergemeinschaftung Heute |trans-title=Living in Scenes. Forms of Youth Communities |language=German |year=2010 |publisher=VS Verlag f\u00fcr Sozialwissenschaften GmbH |isbn=9783531925325 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GNsdBAAAQBAJ |accessdate=2013-06-23}}\n* {{cite thesis |type=Ph.D. |first=Andrew |l